Prophecy<br>
-------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
<br>
Creapiing looked up from the latest reports on her desk. A casual motion and the apprentice approached her with a new stack of documents. Another long dismal night of paperwork awaited her, and she looked longingly at her new Wurmslayer, and daydreamed of an epic battle. Some day the harvest would Slay a great dragon, and that was the weapon she would weild.<br>
<br>
Startled by a noise she looked up to see the Mad One approaching. Prophet? Unusual to see you so sober, is something amiss?<br>
<br>
====================================<br>
<br>
Nospiratus<br>
The Mad Prophet<br>
(1/11/01 12:04:13 pm)<br>
<br>
Re: Prophecy<br>
-------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
<br>
Gold enshrouded by a simple charcoal-gray cloak, Nospiratus entered the room stiff from a sleepless night, head aching from the torment of his Master's whimsy. Exhausted red eyes peered at the Reaper from across her desk as he sat down heavily in the new, hobbit-hide chair. He began to speak, then paused and rubbed his temples. He thought to reach for his flask, but decided against it for the moment.<br>
<br>
&quot;Speak old friend, what is on your mind?&quot;<br>
<br>
Any that knew her could tell that the casual urging was slightly more than it seemed, yet Nospiratus paused a moment longer.<br>
<br>
Finally, he had his few wits cornered long enough to form coherent sentences.<br>
<br>
&quot;Reaper, we have a problem.&quot;<br>
<br>
The knight glanced at the papers seemingly strewn in randomness across her desk and smiled slowly. &quot;Prophet, we have many problems. The grain shipments we expected from the Karanas have not been procured yet, the quartermasters are in a tiff about the current shortage of quality whetstones, and there seems to be a shortage of linseed oil!&quot; The Reaper peered at the priest and leaned back in her chair and grimaced. &quot;And I miss my old chair.&quot;<br>
<br>
Nospiratus sat in a daze, and if he heard a word she said, he gave no indication. Instead, he stood rapdly and moved toward the exit. The Repaer cocked her head and watched him staggger forward, but she was silent. He was always a strange fellow, but this behavior was more than odd - it was unsettling.<br>
<br>
At the doorway, still scorched and awaiting the carpenter's skills, he leaned against a blackened frame and whispered in the tongue of the Combine Alliance. Creapiing leaned forward and was barely able to catch the words.<br>
<br>
&quot;...for out of the frost and frozen breath the form and menace of his hand shall stretch. Never seen and never heard they all shall fade without a word. All shall fade without a word, those who strive against us all - those of sheltering shadowfall. The Cup their death, brought by her breath.&quot;<br>
<br>
Nospiratus sank to his knees, and the Reaper called for her servants and sprang forward. Grasping his hair in her hands, she turned his head and locked his gaze with her own.<br>
<br>
&quot;What does this mean Prophet!&quot;<br>
<br>
A slow, mad smile crept across his face and his eyes gleamed with insane delight. She dropped his head and stepped back, for the light of Hate was pure within his eyes. For a moment she thought she saw grim, stone streets within his dilated pupil, but then they focused and he laughed. The reaper stood and stared, as the servants ran forward to assist the Prophet. Still he stared at her and laughed with such a joyless sound as she had never before heard. Her office seemed suddenly cold, and she could see her breath escaping in a frosted mist.<br>
<br>
She stared after his departing form, listening to his madness, pondering his words. Insane babble or prophecy? She did not know - she was simply Hate's blade. But the words echoed in her mind like an unshakeable nightmare.<br>
<br>
